>I recently heard of a mental disorder called Obsessive Compulsiv>Disorder.  What is it?  What causes it?  Could it be caused by >nervous breakdown>Obesssive Compulsive Disorder (not to be confused with Obsessive Compulsiv_Personality_ Disorder !) is an acute anxiety disorder characterized beither obsessions (persistent intrusive thoughts that cause anxiety whenot entertained), or compulsions (repetitive, ritualistic actions thasimilarly cause intense psychological discomfort when resisted). OCD is often associated with certain forms of depression. Examples of obsessive thoughts are repeated impulses to kill a loveone (though not accompanied by anger), or a religious person havingrecurrent blasphemous thoughts.  Generally, the individual attempts to ignoror suppress the intrusive thoughts by engaging in other activities. The individual realizes that the thoughts originate from the own mind, rathethan being from an external sourceExamples of compulsive actions are constant repetitive hand washingor other activity that is not realistically related to alleviating source of the anxietyIn OCD, the obsessions or compulsions are highly distressing to thindividual, take an hour or more per day, and significantly impair theidaily routine and social relationshipsTreatments include psychotherapy, behavioral methods, and sometimecertain anti-depressants which have recently been found effective in alleviatinobsessions and compulsionsThe standard diagnostic code for OCD, if you want to look it up in thDSM-III manual of psychiatric diagnosis is 300.30 \t\t\t\t\t\tkind regards\t\t\t\t\t\ttod+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------| Todd I. Stark\t\t\t\t  stark@dwovax.enet.dec.com           | Digital Equipment Corporation\t\t             (215) 354-1273           | Philadelphia, Pa. USA                                                       |    "(A word is) the skin of a living thought"  Olliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.  +-----------------------------